Per AWS behavior, if an improper access policy file is used when uploading a policy to a role, the following error is returned:
{code}
error (MalformedPolicyDocument): Policy document should not specify a principal.
{code}
This error is returned when there is a 'Principal' element in the access policy.
Eucalyptus returns the following:
{code}
[root@odc-f-13 ~]# euare-roleuploadpolicy -r describe-instances -p describe-instances-v1 -f role-describe-instances-v1.json --region account1-user01@
euare-roleuploadpolicy: error (MalformedPolicyDocument): Error in uploaded policy: {
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Action": [
                "ec2:DescribeInstances"
            ],
            "Principal": {
                "AWS": "408396244283"
            },
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:*:408396244283:instance/*"
        }
    ]
}
{code}

Steps to Reproduce:
Set up Eucalyptus 4.0.1 Cloud
Create account, group and user using euare commands
Create a role using the following trust policy document (which is attached):
{code}
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": { "Service": "ec2.amazonaws.com"},
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
    }
  ]
}
{code}
[root@odc-f-13 ~]# euare-rolecreate -r describe-instances -f role-trust.json --region account1-user01@
[root@odc-f-13 ~]# euare-rolelistbypath --region account1-user01@
arn:aws:iam::408396244283:role/describe-instances
Try to upload the role-describe-instances-v1.json policy file using euare-roleuploadpolicy:
{code}
[root@odc-f-13 ~]# euare-roleuploadpolicy -r describe-instances -p describe-instances-v1 -f role-describe-instances-v1.json --region account1-user01@
euare-roleuploadpolicy: error (MalformedPolicyDocument): Error in uploaded policy: {
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Action": [
                "ec2:DescribeInstances"
            ],
            "Principal": {
                "AWS": "408396244283"
            },
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:*:408396244283:instance/*"
        }
    ]
}
{code}

Workaround: Remove the 'Principal' element, and set the 'Resource' element to a wildcard (i.e. "*"), in the access policy document. For example:
{code}
{
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Action": [
                "ec2:DescribeInstances"
            ],
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Resource": "*"
        }
    ]
}
{code}

[~hspencer] I am not sure this is actually a bug. In 4.1. I do not get an error at all with the following and the policy does get uploaded
{code}
[c-21:~]euare-roleuploadpolicy -r describe-instances -p describe-instances-policy -f role-describe-instances-principle.json --region test-account-test-user@
[c-21:~]euare-rolelistpolicies -r describe-instances
describe-instances-policy
IsTruncated: false
{code}

The error you were seeing in SUP-517  was :
{code}
com.eucalyptus.auth.PolicyParseException: net.sf.json.JSONException: 'arn:aws:ec2:*:408396244283:instance/*' is not a valid ARN
{code}

We no longer see this error in 4.1 as we Iallow a wildcard for the region '*' See EUCA-9962. Did you test this against AWS?

[~hspencer] My point here is that if you remove the principle in 4.0.2 and use the following json 
{code}
"Statement": [
        {
            "Action": [
                "ec2:DescribeInstances"
            ],
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:*:408396244283:instance/*"
        }
    ]
{code} 
You will still get the error "net.sf.json.JSONException: 'arn:aws:ec2:*:408396244283:instance/*' is not a valid ARN".  You will not get an error with or without the principle in 4.1.  You are getting an error in 4.0.x because of the wildcard in the resource arn not because of the Principle. The fix for EUCA-9970 addresses all cases where the MalformedPolicyDocument error is thrown with the policy text instead of the error message. In 4.1 there is no error thrown at all for euare-roleuploadpolicy using the following  json:
{code}
{
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Action": [
                "ec2:DescribeInstances"
            ],
            "Principal": {
                "AWS": "408396244283"
            },            
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:*:408396244283:instance/*"
        }
    ]
}
{code}

